It is documented at [doc](http://expressjs.com/guide.html#intro) as below:

``` JavaScript

app.get('/hello.txt', function(req, res){
  var body = 'Hello World';
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
  res.setHeader('Content-Length', body.length);
  res.end(body);
});

```

It is right. However, since strings are UTF-8 in default, it might be better using `Buffer.byteLength(body, 'utf-8')` instead of `body.length`.

Consider this code:

``` JavaScript

var body = 'hello, ä¸­æ–‡å­—';
body.length; // oops, it's 10
Buffer.byteLength(body, 'utf-8') // good, 16.

```

HTTP protocol says ["When a Content-Length is given in a message where a message-body is allowed, its field value MUST exactly match the number of OCTETs in the message-body."](http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#section-4.4). It is okay when I test using curl, but some HTTP clients only accept correct length, for example Qt's QNetworkReply. (tested under Mac OSX 10.9, Qt 5.2.0) So I think it's better to provide a right value.

Using `body.lenth` in the doc is NOT wrong, but may lead to some misunderstanding to beginners. I suggest to change it to `Buffer.byteLength(body, 'utf-8')`.

